Comment:
@willieearles3151  That's because this batman still hasn't  created his charismatic, classy, playboy "Bruce Wayne persona" YET, Pattinson was explaining this at the DcFandome panel, that this batman doesn't know how to separate Bruce from Batman, so he gets lost in Batman... it's part of his character arc, his character development, he's gonna have to realize that he needs to create his "Bruce Wayne persona" .This explains his long hair, his seriousness even when he doesn't have his batman suit and it's in public, because even without the suit he's still pretty much Batman and not his alter ego (the playboy Bruce Wayne).. 

This has happen in several Batman comics, in which the character start without that "Bruce Wayne persona" and later on he creates one.

If you watched Tenet (it doesn't matter if you didn't like the movie, if you thought the movie was too confusing, too plot driven, bc I'm only going to mention one scene ) then you know there is a scene where  Pattinson's character, Neil, had to pretend to be a wealthy man, while at the same time he was carefully observing his surroundings, planning an operation on his head, but, keeping his facade, his well trim, elegant, classy and charismatic demeanor. In that scene Neil resembles Bruce Wayne, my point is that Robert knows how to play, a wealthy well trim, elegant/classy and charismatic character, he knows how to be a Bruce Wayne, if he is not doing it here, is because it doesn't serve the story YET because he hasn't created his "Bruce Wayne persona," but  eventually  will do it...  And this is Matt Reeves vision, because he has said so himself, Pattinson is only playing the role in the way Reeves envisioned the character's journey, changing the actor won't change anything, because that other actor will also play Bruce but without the "Bruce Wayne persona", for the first movie because that's Matt Reeves vision. .. And Robert  Pattinson is a handsome man, always was.

🚨*Sorry for my english, it's  not my native tongue*

Comment: Touch grass. Even the cartoons are better Batman films. This is a pretentious, artsy, pseudo-intellectual mess of a movie that tries too hard to take It self too seriously while being full of stupid and goofy, and most importantly fails at being what Batman movies are meant to be - engaging. Nothing about It feels satisfying, there's nothing original about the plot, there's no character development, by the end everything pretty much stays the same. Now we know that in the next movie Joker will be in It and we're supposed to be super excited about that tease, because It's not like we've seen enough iterations of that character already. Why explore anything different? Just to be clear the movie is not terrible, but it's not the masterpiece people say It is. If you seriously believe that you have a lot of movies to explore.

author: @shaunthenomad

Comment:
@dartaianfreire  uhhhhh not really.
That’s not “slight references to seven” in the way that you mean.
Having a rainy weather and a serial killer isn’t a reference to seven at all, that’s usually how a hard boiled film noir detective movie usually is, this kind gritty dark tones is a pull into the genre of “murder mystery detective stories” that which Batman the character was FAR before seven even existed as Batman was a big character in “detective comics”.
You act like seven was the first one to do it like this but it wasn’t, seven was the first to have a incredibly modern neo noir murder mystery street that was as dark and as brutal as it was but not the other aspect.
Rain is a super common trope that happens all the time in film noir detective stories so that’s not a reference to just one movie at all.

Having “mind games” is riddler’s whole gimmick and aspect that he does which AGAIN is something that came before seven was even at thing.

I’m not saying this movie isn’t paying homage to seven in anyway because I’m sure it does with the super dark and gritty tone is something that’s it’s trying to aim for as seven seems like the world of Gotham before Batman got there’re as Seven and Batman go hand and hand completely but the examples your saying isn’t entirely references to it but it’s more of common tropes that you see in noir detective stories but the movie Seven REALLY pushed it on what the movie can do.

Comment:
LMAO what? Do you know NOTHING about Batman at all? This isn’t a “revenge” story at all, Batman calls himself “vengeance” because he’s angry at criminals and crime itself that negatively effects people as he’s heavily traumatized by his parent’s death by a criminal so he’s a on a “vengeance ” crusade lifestyle against all criminals to stop crime without killing anyone. This is Batman 101 if you know the character at all.

You’re not making much sense as Batman is all about violence as he’s a dark character whose still a hero and he’s GOING to have to use violence to stop criminals who need to be beat down BUT this movie isn’t “exaggerated violence” at all as it’s all perfectly brutal and violence to showcase the grim dark life of Gotham city.
And this movie is MAINLY a about trauma and how to overcome it.

 It IS "action packed" but it's not OVERT with the action for it to be ALL about that throughout the film. While this movie is aiming more for Detective crime solving aspect for it to be a psychological thriller (which I LOVE to death as FINALLY Batman gets to showcase he's the "World's greatest detective"), it UNIQUELY does it PHENOMENALLY by combination of it still being a superhero film that makes vastly unique from other Batman movies entirely!

And this movie HAS angry and traumatized characters and it’s all done in a PHENOMENAL way that explains the troubles of Gotham and how it effects people living there, and Batman is there to save others from it all.
If this movie even WAS classified as a “revenge story” which it’s NOT, it’s a MASSIVELY unique about a dark hero whose the light of a grim city and trying to save its people. FAR from any kind of “revenge story” at all.
This movie is a 10/10 MASTERPIECE and THE BEST Batman to date.
If you loved Dune (which I did as well as that Movie is a MASTERPIECE as well) your going to most likely love this as well.
Their both 10/10 Masterpiece movies in their field.

Comment: @m0n4rch911  If you watch the behind the scenes you will understand that this film takes inspiration from Batman year one. The theme of the film is literally going to be character development. If you’ve ever read Batman year one, you understand just how “edgy”, emo, and gritty Bruce Wayne truly is. It’s psychology breaking and this movie’s budget is literally 80 million less than The Dark Knight. That’s even more proof that this movie will focus on “story” or writing than just cool Batman features and flashy superheroness. It’s supposed to be a realistic adaptation of a comic. The comics this movie is supposed to take inspiration from is exactly why true DC fans are going to be so happy with this film because Batman Year One is one of the greatest comics ever written and the Long Halloween is a eye opening moral awakening. This Batman is in his second year. Comment: @k-b9253  I think the most interesting part of batman is his anger, the fact that he’s so close to the line that separates him from the people he fights, but never quite crosses it. I’m a fan of stories like Arkham asylum serious house, which really exaggerate and showcase Batman’s broken, tortured mental state, as appose to stories like batman year one which portray a more stoic, stern version of the character. Don’t get me wrong, I love year one and that version of batman is needed, he’s great. Just look at 3 of the four Arkham games and the dark knight trilogy, it’s brilliant, but I guess that’s the thing, that version of batman is very oversaturated. I think we need more stories like batman Serious house and batman Arkham origins, that really show off the moral and psychological complexities of the character, so I really should have put “this is everything I WANT batman to be”, as appose to “everything batman should be”. Another thing to note is, this Batman’s brutality won’t be left unexplored like Ben afleck’s portrayal, which came off as thuggish and not at all like batman; the synopsis of the film indicates that a lot of attention will be put on Batman’s anger, talking about his struggle between veangence and righteousness, which is personally something I am so hyped for.

There's no positive and negative emotions, happiness can be negative and sadness can be positive. There's emotions are generic...

author: @galactic85

Comment:
@akmal94ibrahim  Yes a man of culture! I love that scene!!! The photography and framing that Zack synder used to convey batman in a nightmarish way as a creature is incredible!!

The music, the slow foreboding tense build up of the cop talking to the prisoners, then discovering the criminal then realising batman is perched up in the corner behind him. Also in BvS: UE there’s a scene where lex is watching security footage of batman scooping up a security guard in a hallway, up into a ventilation shaft whilst other officers fire back in retaliation. As the footage is black and white from our perspective and lex’s it looked supernatural.

Imagine watching footage of a dark black figure with glowing white eyes jumping down from the ceiling then kidnapping a human and jumping back up disappearing.... 😱😱😱😱😱😱🙀🙀🙀🙀🙀🙀
NOW THAT’S BATMAN!!!!

@thorny8013  lol are you for real? This movie WAS vastly much more intense as the trailers and EVEN MORE SO, you saying that its not is failing to understand the movie at all. It DID pick up the pace during action scenes entirely that DID make everyone go “whoa this is intense” completely so, because all the fights were grounded in a street level way that Batman was able to take on multiple guys at once but he had to work for it as nothing came easy for him in the film at all which was fantastic and phenomenal to see! Comment:
@sathvik6982  that’s where we disagree. I think Batman is a great character when his strengths are played to and the narrative surrounding him is honest not meta

Batman was created one year after Superman, right at the end of what’s know as the Golden Age of Detective Fiction but he was already an established character by the time teenage boys fascination moved from the intrepid explorers and detectives of dime store pulp comics like Buck Rogers and The Hardy Boys to the glossy pages of Action Comics and Timely Comics w/ their superhumans in bright patriotic leotards

In fact DC used to literally be Detective Comics. All that is to say that yes Batman is a character of a different age but so is Superman, Wonder Woman, Captain America, X Men etc. I don’t think that matters. What matters is what you do w/ the characters NOW. Every other comicbook character has stayed true to their origins more or less w/ just updated goals, values and designs to match the changing times. Every character except Batman

I’m not saying Batman is a bad character what I’m saying is he deserves a lot more than writers constantly smashing him and other characters together like mis matched action figures w/ the obligatory smile and wink to the audience while they make jokes about none of it making sense. Somehow 82 years of prep time still couldn’t save him from that

Comment:
A lot of people are saying that they didn't really include new rogues gallery characters because they've all been in previous films. But that's a blatant technicality, comparing the Riddler we've had until now to this one is essentially a different character all-together, as was Catwoman to a lesser degree. Much like the Riddler the Penguin was shown in a far different (and more realistic) light and though we've heard about Falcone in the other movies this is the first time he was actually important to the arching narrative.

Though I will say to everyone stating "I'm glad it wasn't the Joker again" or "They can't do the Joker after Heath Ledger" did like...any of you see the scene between him and the Riddler at the end? It's pretty obvious he'll be coming back so we can never really escape him.

Honestly I want a proper Scarecrow. He was in Nolans films but he was a bit player and his intelligence was really underplayed. Scarecrow rarely works for anyone but himself and in this new, darker take on the IP we could finally get the truly terrifying Scarecrow that we've gotten in the comics.

Comment:
@robertogurrola7465  Batman has always been an emo character, plus the only reason Pattinson's Bruce Wayne is more "emo or edgy like" it's because this batman still hasn't  created his classy, well trim, charismatic, playboy "Bruce Wayne persona" YET,  Matt Reeves and Pattinson explained this at the DcFandome panel.* .. He (Bruce) doesn't have interest in being Bruce, he's operating almost  completely just in Batman mode,* in this first movie, this is part of his character arch, he's gonna have to realize that he needs to create his "Bruce Wayne persona,"  This explains his long hair, his seriousness even when he doesn't have his batman suit on and it's in public, because even without the suit he's still pretty much Batman and not his alter ego (the playboy Bruce Wayne). that this Batman doesn't fully know (but eventually will know) what he's doing, doesn't know how to separate Bruce from Batman so he gets lost in the batman character. How to control his rage and anger will also form part of his character arc.

in several Batman comics this has happened " It's his second y*ear as Batman, he's flawed, he needs to learn that he has to better himself as Bruce and also as Batman.* .. This is Matt Reeves vision, because Reeves has said so himself, Pattinson is playing the role in the way Reeves envisioned the character's journey


He said this Batman takes every fight personally, because he ( batman) is full of rage, and he doesn't know exactly how to control it yet, or what to do, he needs to learn ... This will also be part of his character arc, he starts like a rageful Batman (in the comics Batman was brutal in his first years) and later in the trilogy he becomes in the batman we know.

Comment:
My favourite parts of the trailer (aside from all of it!)
1. THAT SCORE OMG
2. This sort of unhinged Batman. Almost as though he could belong in Arkham with the rest of the crazies
3. This serial killer, Zodiac-esqu Riddler. Really helps this feel more like a detective film with action, which is fitting for someone titled 'the world's greatest detective'
4. The Batmobile. Less flashy and ridiculous than past versions yet not as militaristic as the Tumbler. It's like some ungodly crossover between retro 80s supercar and classic muscle car, with a good helping of Mad Max thrown in for good measure. It remains both sleek and brutish and I am IN LOVE

Bruce Wayne is a traumatized orphan with the weight of his family's business on his shoulders. Being Batman is his way of releasing that stress; the kind of release that an immature young man can't resist or control.

Comment: It's how people are trained to shoot, and basic common sense. The torso is the biggest target on the human body, and filled with almost all your most vital organs. And the natural upward motion of recoil means if you start low, each successive shot would still probably land further up the torso and even into the neck/head. Aiming for the bottom half of a guy's face, especially in low visibility conditions, is both stupid and wasteful.

Comment:
@christisking835  Sure but I’d saying that Robert Pattinson has EASILY perfect as Batman AND Bruce Wayne aa the BEST of both as he was able to showcase what makes Batman who he is, his trauma. It’s not really that he’s “depressed” in this movie, it’s that he’s heavily TRAUMATIZED in it and that’s the motivation that makes Batman who he is.
He LEARNS how to be better Bruce Wayne AND Batman at the end of this movie, as this was the whole point OF the movie.
Bruce's Trauma has deeply effected his entire life and well being. It's not about trying to portray a "play boy bachelor" at all, it's about showing a gloomy individual whose DEEPLY traumatized from his parent's death that he can't think or do anything else and I LOVE the way how it's done as Bruce can't be batman without his trauma but this still it's consumed his life so much that he's never moved past his parent's passing to have his own life. This Bruce Wayne looks like he's never had a girlfriend, much less slept with another girl, and DESPERATELY needs to leave his house and touch some grass and it's PERFECT! It's COMPLETELY perfect because Batman IS Bruce's trauma, and this movie had to showcase that he's so obsessed with being batman that he forget how to be himself and a proper human being. It's no different from Batman: Year One or Batman: Mask of the Phantasm, Batman IS the Trauma that makes Batman, BATMAN.
Batman's story will ALWAYS be a tragedy at heart as he can never be fully happy to be Batman.
But the point of this movie is showcase how Bruce can LEARN how to grow from that with his interactions with Selina so he can be a human again and learn HOW to be a better Batman for the people of Gotham by not being so full of rage but by being an inspiration of hope and love!

Comment:
Maybe Nolan is a better director and has a better movie overall, but The Batman is a better Batman film. Not a perfect Batman film, not a perfect adaptation, but closer to the source material and who Batman is. 

Nolan's trilogy would’ve been miles better if it didn’t sometimes stray away from the comics too much. 
There were many great and unique takes on Batman's supporting characters in Nolan's trilogy, but Batman himself was several times ruined and compromised as a character.
author: @wserthmar8908

Comment: The Nolan movies played a massive part in bringing Batman as a character back into the live action mainstream. The way I see this movie is being a grounded interpretation of what Bruce would have been like in his early days. People respect and loge Batman because of how humans he is, yet in films they expect him to be superhuman. Batman’s ‘superpower’ has always been his wealth as a baseline, but also his relentless determination and ingenuity. In a more grounded fictional world, you can’t expect him to become a legend overnight. To me this feels like a refreshing portrayal of what Batman and his first steps into greatness would realistically look like, especially in a live action portrayal.

Comment: Thursday, October 31st. The city streets are crowded for the holiday. Even with the rain. Hidden in the chaos is the element, waiting to strike like snakes. And I'm there too. Watching. 2 years of nights have turned me into a nocturnal animal. I must choose my targets carefully. It's a big city. I can't be everywhere. But they don't know where I am. We have a signal now, for when I'm needed. When that light hits the sky, it's not just a call- it's a warning. To them. Fear is a tool. They think I'm hiding in the shadows. But I AM the shadows. I wish I could say I'm making a difference, but I don't know. Murder, robberies, assault- 2 years later, they're all up. And now this. This city's eating itself. Maybe it can't be saved, but i have to try. PUSH MYSELF. These nights all roll together in a rush, Behind the mask. Sometimes in the morning i have to force myself to remember everything that happened.

Comment:
I just watched it for the second time ever last week after seeing it in the theaters.  It’s up there with Dredd and Blade Runner 2049 for me as far as theater experiences, the only way i describe them is spellbinding.

The depth of this movie is what makes it the best Batman.  Christopher Nolan took it there and the Dark Knight trilogy will stand alone, but this Matt Reaves rendition already set a tone that is already unmatched.  Robert Pattinson blew me away with his take on the tortured, isolative and emotionally stunted person the real Bruce Wayne would have had to be to be true to the character of an orphan child.  Some of the mannerisms were played a little too well it’s like authentic lyrics from a traumatized artist. 

I felt like this wasn’t dark just to be dark and it wasn’t trying to be colorful at all to live up to the hype, but still it was unrelenting in its depictions of the rich history of all the comics, the animated versions, and our real world, the comics are based on, especially right now with mental illness and public corruption coming to ahead. I am excited to see this version develop and really hope they work in the League of Shadows after the Joker in a nod to Nolan, and the immortal Ras lol.

Comment: Wow, so much to say/think about this edition of the Dark Knight. I remember days of classic cartoons featuring Batman, like "Challenge of the Superfriends" and the Adam West Burt Ward TV show with the great color-costumes of live-action pow, and then came Tim Burton and the Animated Series (on Fox), which were watershed! Christopher Nolan and Ben Affleck gave it nice spice no doubt too. This one featuring the Riddler is both eerie, jarring, graphic, dark, pensive, Realism and neo-modern with classic touches here and there. Jeffrey Wright is good in this too, good supporting character IMO. Batman's surpassed Captain America, no? Batman is officially the strangest super-hero out there. I compare this worlds-graphics trend in Batman-media to the turn we saw with classic (Laurel and Hardy) to modern (Farrelly Bros.) comedy imagery...all humanist. Quite cool.

Comment: The Batman, skillfully directed by Matt Reeves, offers a captivating cinematic experience. I appreciate the darker approach Reeves took with Robert Pattinson's portrayal. Drawing inspiration from Tim Burton's iconic Batman films of 1989 and 1992, which established a gothic and brooding atmosphere with Michael Keaton in the lead, Reeves masterfully sets a similar tone. The ensemble cast and crew deliver stellar performances, with Zoe Kravitz shining in her role, Colin Farrell transforming into a mesmerizing Penguin - his portrayal so convincing, one could hardly recognize him - and Jeffrey Wright delivering a compelling performance as James Gordon. It would be intriguing to witness Joaquin Phoenix embody the Joker in a potential sequel, pitting his talents against Pattinson's Batman.

Comment: I’m just writing down what I’m literally thinking now. This batman hopefully WAS just trained by Alfred, and he’s still this good. Just a better detective. What if the second movie, he travelled the world and became more refined! Comes back to Gotham with a new upbeat and confident attitude as Bruce, and as Batman he’s more about saving than revenge. I’m not sure who could take him on, but not Joker yet. Ra’s? Anyway this gives him a good reason to be more of a ninja lmao but also it plays more into the “I am the Night” than a “I am Vengeance” and that’s good for movie number two, as the old catchphrase goes. I hope they modify his suit too, to reflect that change in attitude. I think these ideas would get us to a closer more accurate Batman and we could finish off the trilogy with the last line “I am Batman” seeing him go through all his stages of being Batman lol, but also these ideas I think make justifiable sense from the first movie (like Bruce obviously being Batman, but switching his Bruce persona up a bit to disguise thag problem. It’s a movie too, I mean Batman travelling around the world and becoming the number one badass isn’t realistic prolly, but I wanna see it! I like where it’s going either way, but wouldn’t it be awesome to see Pattinson as a live action Arkham batman sort of lmfao idk I just want some badass fight scenes next time around. This guy is the peak of all humans, I wanna see it
